Intro to Storybook

Storybook is a development tool that loads components in isolation from the application as a whole.

These “stories” allow developers to load and interact with component variants without having to get the full application into a specific state for those variants to show.

For example, you can configure a Storybook Story for things like an already opened modal or a checkout form with a coupon code already applied.

Storybook exists somewhere in between manual and automated testing. It’s great for doing quick tests with the keyboard and screen reader. I’ve also found I feel better prepared to write unit tests when I’m able interact with only the component I’m interested in testing. It’s much less distracting than seeing it in the context of a full page.

Configuring Storybook

Storybook uses its own Webpack configuration that can be found at .storybook/main.js.

The configuration object includes an entry for stories that takes an array of paths to the various component stories. In this setup, we tell it to look for a file that includes .stories. in its name with any of the common component file extensions:

"stories": [
    "../**/*.stories.@(js|jsx|ts|tsx)",
  ],
"stories": [
    "../**/*.stories.@(js|jsx|ts|tsx)",
  ],

Aliases to the components and data directories have also been configured to save on typing later.

We also tap into Storybook’s Webpack configuration to allow for CSS variables and images to be used in the individual component stories.

Using Storybook

To start Storybook, run the following command as seen in the scripts section of package.json:

yarn storybook

After a few seconds to spin things up, Storybook will open its UI in a new browser tab at http://localhost:6006.

Storybook has a sidebar on the left that has been pre-configured to include components and pages from the CampSpots demo application. Clicking one of these options will display it in the main screen to the right.

The starting point of this lesson has been configured to include individual stories for several components including the DatePicker, ListingExcerpt, and MegaNav.

There may be times where loading a component in Storybook will have styles applied differently than they would be when viewing the component in the actual application.

For example, the SearchForm component has CSS Grid properties applied when loaded in a full page of the application that are not applied in its Storybook story.

Edit Data in the Controls Pane

Storybook gives you the option to supply different test data than what is in production. This gives you a chance to test how flexible your components are while having a bit of fun with it.

You can supply default values, or change them on the fly in Storybook’s Controls pane.

View a Component in Full Screen

By default, Storybook loads each component story inside of an iframe, as seen in this screenshot from Chrome DevTools:

Screen reader testing when there are iframes and the additional stuff from the Storybook UI would be pretty cumbersome.

Fortunately, Storybook provides a full screen canvas view!

Clicking the icon in the upper right corner of a Story will open that component on its own in a new tab.

The component is rendered in the main document as an HTML snippet without the wrapping iframe, as seen in this screenshot of the ListingExcerpt component:

This full screen view will make screen reader testing of the component much easier.

Identify Issues with the Accessibility Add-on

Storybook offers a wide variety of add-ons that introduce additional functionality. Of particular interest to us is the Accessibility Add-on, which is powered by axe-core.

Installing the Add-on

Install the add-on as a dev dependency by running:

yarn add @storybook/addon-a11y --dev
yarn add @storybook/addon-a11y --dev

Once it's installed, open Storybook's configuration file located at .storybook/main.js.

Inside of the module.exports object should be an "addons" key with an array of package names.

Create a new entry for @storybook/addon-a11y like so:

module.exports = {
  "stories": [...],
  "addons": [
    "@storybook/addon-a11y"
  ]
}
module.exports = {
  "stories": [...],
  "addons": [
    "@storybook/addon-a11y"
  ]
}

Save the file, then restart Storybook by running yarn storybook and refresh the UI.

The Accessibility Add-on Panel

Like many accessibility testing tools, the Storybook a11y add-on uses axe-core behind the scenes to identify issues.

When a violation is found, we are given a brief explanation of the problem and provided with tags that reference WCAG and Section 508 guidelines as well as best practices.

Many of the accessibility issues that would be identified in Storybook could be caught earlier in the development process, but it’s still an add-on that’s well worth installing.

Note: In this video, there was an issue with icons displaying in Storybook, but this has been fixed in the project repo.

📝 Exercise: Add Storybook to Your Own Project

We’ll add additional components and configuration to Storybook as this module progresses. For now try adding Storybook to your own project.

Reference the official docs and the CampSpots repo’s configuration for help!
